a crime, with modest efforts being undertaken to address women's health and well being. The available abortion services are provided mainly by state hospitals or private gynecologists. For a large majority of women the range of contraception methods remains inadequate. While women are allowed access to the pharmacies, most women cannot afford better methods of contraception. Women face the double burden and injustice of difficulties in accessing abortion services, and facing high risks of disparities in terms of access to adequate methods of contraception. A young woman can face multiple stigma and prejudice and rightly so - but should we perpetuate this, just because we are either unable or unwilling to address it. As for an effective, secular, fundamental and universal human rights-based system of law and practice - not an easy solution, but it certainly exists and is pragmatic. Equally, for ensuring equality between women and men in marital life, at least as far as secondary effects of their contraceptive practices are concerned – well the story is rather different.

I am referring to the “Directive d’Orientation pour Mettre Fin a la Pratique de l’Electeurcide“, an ethical workplace standard, created following negotiations between trade unions and employers (in 1958) to give effects to the UN Universal Declaration of Human Rights. As may be imagined, Mauritania was by no means an exception at that time, as enshrined on page 34 – section 23 when it reads: Je ne souh.ite pas attendre desujet élèves chose
